<section xml:id="sec_indefinite_integrals_and_antiderivatives">
  <title>Indefinite Integrals and Antiderivatives</title>
  <p>
    If we do not have limits of integration we still can use the <c>Int()</c> and <c>int()</c> commands to show and evaluate the integrals respectively.
  </p>
  <p>
        <idx><h>integral</h><h>int!indefinite</h></idx>
        <idx><h>integral</h><h>Int!indefinite</h></idx>
        <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>square root</h></idx>
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      Recall that <c>Int()</c> displays the integral and <c>int()</c> evaluates the integral.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {Int(sin(x),
    x); } \end{mapleinput} \relax \begin{maplelatex} {Int(sin(x), x)}{
    <me>
      \displaystyle \int \!\sin \left( x \right) {dx}
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    } \end{maplelatex} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {int(sin(x),
    x); } \end{mapleinput} \relax \begin{maplelatex} {-cos(x)}{
    <me>
      \displaystyle -\cos \left( x \right)
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    } \end{maplelatex} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      Maple does not include the addition of the constant of integration <m>+C</m> when evaluating indefinite integrals.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {p(x) := 1/sqrt(1 + x\symbol{94}2); } \end{mapleinput} \relax \begin{maplelatex} {p := proc (x) options operator,
    arrow; 1/sqrt(1+x^2) end proc}{
    <me>
      \displaystyle p\, := \,x\mapsto {\frac {1}{\sqrt {{x}^{2}+1}}}
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    } \end{maplelatex} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {Int(p(x),
    x); } \end{mapleinput} \relax \begin{maplelatex} {Int(1/sqrt(x^2+1), x)}{
    <me>
      \displaystyle \int \! \left(  \sqrt{{x}^{2}+1} \right) ^{-1}{dx}
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    } \end{maplelatex} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      The function arcsinh<m>()</m> is called the inverse hyperbolic sine function.
      Functions like <m>\cosh()</m> and <m>\sinh()</m> are called hyperbolic functions.
      These functions are analogs of the ordinary trigonometric,
      or circular,
      functions;
      just as the points <m>(\cos(t), \sin(t))</m> form a circle with a unit radius,
      the points <m>(\cosh(t), \sinh(t))</m> form the right half of the equilateral hyperbola.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
        <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>inverse hyperbolic sine</h></idx>
        <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>hyperbolic functions!sinh</h></idx>
        <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>hyperbolic functions!cosh</h></idx> \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {int(p(x), x); } \end{mapleinput} \relax \begin{maplelatex} {arcsinh(x)}{
    <me>
      \displaystyle \textit{arcsinh} \left( x \right)
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    } \end{maplelatex} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
